of the texture target to use: it needs to use the external target iff

entry.title: Don't bind a null LayoutText pointer to a reference
entry.content:
https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5308656

introduced a null reference, which is undefined behavior and flagged by

UBSan. If text_layout_object was null, it is UB to write

*text_layout_object. Although the parameter was ignored

(ShouldUpdateLayoutByReattaching will return true and thus

UpdateTextLayoutObject will ignore layout_text), even binding the

reference is too late.



We could fix this by making LayoutText a pointer, but then that method's

API contract is weird because layout_text would need to be non-null when

by_reattach is true. Instead, since this helper method is so short and

only called twice, I've simply inlined it into the two call sites.

entry.title: Invalidate weak pointers in search request before stopping search
entry.content:
Before this CL, only `HandleSearchSourceResults` was guaranteed to be a

no-op after stopping the search - however, the individual

`Handle*SearchResults` methods (one for each search source) were still

called. Any logic inside of those methods - including emitting metrics

and post-processing of results - are still run before calling the

now-no-op `HandleSearchSourceResults`. The only way we guarantee that

`Handle*SearchResults` methods are no-ops is by resetting metrics, so

they do not get emitted in these methods.



Invalidate all weak pointers - and therefore bound callbacks to

`Handle*SearchResults` methods - to ensure that `Handle*SearchResults`

methods are never called in the first place. This prevents the (no-op)

code for emitting metrics, and preprocessing search results (to pass to

a no-op method) from running in the first place.

entry.title: Move search request code from controller to separate class
entry.content:
This separates the responsibilities of aggregation (burn-in) and

ordering - still in the search controller - and performing the requests

to the search sources themselves - now in a new search request class.



This CL is a pure move - the search request class currently has the same

lifetime as the search controller. Future CLs may change the lifetime of

the search request class so it lives for as long as a search itself -

constructed on search start, destructed on search stop.



We will not add tests for the search request class until it is

refactored more. As it is used directly from the search controller, and

we have extensive test coverage on that, most search request class

behaviours are (indirectly) tested from those tests.

can be filled to some of the codec metadata (e.g. temporal index) and

we would like to avoid a client from wrongly referencing invalid

values.

However, this makes a client difficult to handle a dropped frame in

SVC encoding because a client cannot know a spatial layer index.



This CL introduces DropFrameMetadata. It is set if and only if a

frame is dropped. The metadata has useful info for the dropped frame.

It has spatial index so far.

entry.title: TaskAttribution: Change type hierarchy to allocate less
entry.content:
This CL changes the Task Attribution types so that we can propagate the

same ScriptWrappableTaskState object instead of creating a new one

every time:

- TaskAttributionInfo becomes a pure virtual interface. This class

will eventually hold the SoftNavigationContext.



- TaskAttributionInfoImpl is added as the sole implementation of

TaskAttributionInfo. Separating the impl allows us to access

core/ and inherit directly from ScriptWrappableTaskState, which in

turn allows us to propagate that object directly.



- WebSchedulingTaskState is added as a subclass of

ScriptWrappableTaskState that holds subtask-propagatable state

(TaskAttributionInfo) and continuation-only web-scheduling state

(priority and abort sources).



- Finally, we directly propagate TaskAttributionInfo objects when

there is no web scheduling task state to propagate



Note: this deviates a bit from the type hierarchy described in the

design doc because we no longer need to expose both continuation-only

and subtask propagatable task state now that CPED is more robust

(crrev.com/c/5316657).



Design doc:

entry.title: WebApps: Store whole sync proto to prevent losing new fields
entry.content:
Currently we convert a WebAppSpecifics sync proto into several fields

which are stored on the WebApp struct (or its WebAppSpecifics struct) in

memory. When writing to disk or sync we convert back into a

WebAppSpecifics proto. This conversion causes data loss of new fields

and new field values when handled by older clients.



This CL stores the sync proto directly on the WebApp struct so lossy

conversions aren't done and the data is maintained. An exception is that

we still actively convert absent UserDisplayMode values into set values,

and proto2 (which we are using) represents unknown enum values as

absent. A follow-up CL could change this to lazily set UserDisplayMode

values instead, in order to preserve new enum values.



Bug: b:320769909

entry.title: Add Bluetooth LE Audio support
entry.content:
This CL adds the necessary change to allow chromium to recognize and

connect to Bluetooth LE Audio enabled devices.



Android supports 2 BT connections at once. Since LE Audio is a

separate Bluetooth profile than "classic" BT, this CL originally

tracked each profile separately, in case of multiple devices being

connected at once. However, `getAvailableCommunicationDevices()` only

returns the last connected BT device, regardless of whether it is a

"classic" or "LE" device. This means that we cannot target a specific

device when 2 are connected, and it's simpler to conflate the status of

both profiles.

entry.title: [OOPIF PDF] Use the PDF embedder host for saving URL using PDF UI
entry.content:
Use the PDF embedder host instead of the PDF content host when saving

the URL using the PDF UI.



PDFDocumentHelper is initialized when the PDF content host binds the

PDF service, so PDFDocumentHelper::render_frame_host() should reference

the PDF content host. OOPIF PDF was incorrectly using that host to

save the URL, when it should have been using the PDF embedder host.



This went undetected, since

PdfDownloadTestSplitCacheEnabled.SaveSubframePdfFromPdfUI_IsolationInfo

was incorrectly using the PDF embedder host to create the

PDFDocumentHelper.



Using the PDF content host instead of the embedder host would result in

incorrect network::ResourceRequest::TrustedParams.

entry.title: Remove unused VR UI code
entry.content:
Cleans up some more VR UI code that's unused. A few notable changes:



LinearLayout::layout_length_ was only set in UTs so was 0 in production.

This means that some of it's overrides were not necessary, and were

removed.



Extensive cleanup was done to UiElement to remove methods that were

unused (i.e. not called outside UTs), including several virtual methods

with no overrides. Virtual methods with no overrides and no impl in the

base class were deleted, whereas virtual methods with no overrides but

an impl were marked as non-virtual. This included removing a bunch of

logic for HitTests, Clipping and EventHandling that were tested in UTs

but not used outside of them as well as a few setters who were either

always set to the default value or the set value was never actually

read.



Also removed ControllerModel and TextureCopyRenderer which were

fully unused, as well as cleaning up the UiElementType enum.



Finally, removed some values from ColorScheme that weren't referenced

anywhere. A future cleanup can look at taking ColorScheme away from

being an object to just being a set of static values in a namespace.



Though not yet built for Android, it looks like this should shave off

~5kb from https://crrev.com/c/5324885

entry.title: [RasterInducingScroll] cc::DrawScrollingContentsOp
entry.content:
DrawScrollingContentsOp contains the the following field:

- scroll_element_id identifying a scroller;

- display_item_list containing the painted result of the scrolling

contents of the scroller in the coordinate space of the scrolling

contents;

- main_scroll_offset: the current main-thread scroll offset. This is

currently used when we serialize or rasterize the

DrawScrollingContentsOp to translate the scrolling contents by the

scroll offset. In the next steps, we'll use the impl-side scroll

offsets when we serialize or rasterize the scrolling contents in

the impl thread. This field will still be used if we serialize or

rasterize for other purposes.



DrawScrollingContentsOp will be translated into real paint operations

of the scrolling contents when it's serialized or rasterized.

entry.title: brightness: Save local_state pref for brightness percent
entry.content:
This CL creates a new pref name called

kInternalDisplayScreenBrightnessPercent.



This CL also updates BrightnessControllerChromeos to save the current

brightness value to local state prefs (using the key

kInternalDisplayScreenBrightnessPercent) on login and when the screen

brightness changes.



The new behavior for saving prefs is as follows:

- On the login screen, when the brightness is changed, save the new

brightness value into LocalState prefs (using KnownUser, keyed on

current AccountID, obtained from "OnFocusPod" (i.e. the currently-

selected user on the login screen)).

- When a user logs in, get the current screen brightness and save that

to LocalState prefs (using KnownUser).

- During a user session, when the screen brightness changes due to user

action, save the new brightness value into LocalState prefs (using

KnownUser).



Diagram showing when prefs are saved into prefs (diagram also includes

reading from the prefs, which is not added in this CL):

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/5NXEg7GmNReiWhs



loaded for multiple users
